## Example 2 — Prove a Quadrilateral Is a Parallelogram

A quadrilateral has vertices $A(1, 1)$, $B(5, 1)$, $C(7, 4)$, $D(3, 4)$. Prove it is a parallelogram.

### Step 1: Find the Slopes of Opposite Sides

$$\text{slope of } AB = \frac{1 - 1}{5 - 1} = \frac{0}{4} = 0$$

$$\text{slope of } DC = \frac{4 - 4}{7 - 3} = \frac{0}{4} = 0$$

$$AB \parallel DC \quad (\text{both have slope } 0)$$

$$\text{slope of } AD = \frac{4 - 1}{3 - 1} = \frac{3}{2}$$

$$\text{slope of } BC = \frac{4 - 1}{7 - 5} = \frac{3}{2}$$

$$AD \parallel BC \quad (\text{both have slope } \frac{3}{2})$$

### Step 2: Conclude

Both pairs of opposite sides are parallel, so $ABCD$ is a parallelogram.

✅ Answer: $ABCD$ is a parallelogram because both pairs of opposite sides have equal slopes.

